
Significant progress has been made in driving enterprise adoption of UBI 9 Minimal and Micro container standards across JPMC. Through a combination of technical leadership, developer enablement, and close collaboration with platform teams, the adoption of legacy RHEL 7 images has been reduced to approximately 2%, while adoption of RHEL 9-based images has increased substantially, strengthening the firm's container security posture and reducing technical debt.

To drive awareness and accelerate adoption, I authored engineering articles published through the Engineering Excellence newsletter, including guidance on adopting Minimal/Micro images (`go/minimal`), which received strong engagement from the developer community. I also led the initiative to make Docker Improvement Presets (DiP) available through the Stylus community edition, enabling developers to modernize Dockerfiles and adopt the latest UBI image families with minimal effort.

Working closely with the Middleware team, I have helped drive the timely release and adoption of updated base image families as new UBI versions become available, ensuring application teams have access to secure and supported container foundations.

In addition, I introduced and championed the use of **jlink** and **multi-stage build patterns** as enterprise best practices, publishing guidance (`jp/slim-containers`) to standardize the creation of lean, optimized container images. These initiatives have delivered measurable reductions in image size, decreased attack surface and CVE exposure, and improved application efficiency, with adoption and impact clearly demonstrated through platform telemetry.
